{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657384/1923091901/0414.xml":{"full_text":"CATHEDRAL CROWD\nTO HEAR PEPPER\nSenator and Bishop Freeman\nMass Meeting Speakers;\nPershing Invited.\nThe National Cathedral open-air\nmass meeting on Sunday afternoon,\ni September 30, will be addressed by\nSenator George Wharton Pepper of\nPennsylvania and Bishop James E.\nfreeman. The announcement today\nsaid that if bis duties permit Gen.\nJohn J. Pershing will also make an\nt address.\n'The services will open at 3:30\no'clock, beginning with the hymn of\npraise, which has been the traditional\nopening of such services since the\nfirst service at the cathedral. At that\nmoment the head of the procession,\nwhich will form in St. Alban s\nChurch, will be at the peace cross\nand will wend its way through the\nprocessional aisle toward the ampl\ntheater platform, where a flaming red\ncross of dahlias will be' placed. The\nboys\u2019 choir will precede the Army\nHand of seventy-five pieces, after\nwhich will come a chords of 500\nvoices. The rest of the ecclesiastical\nprocession will follow.\nParking of Automobile*.\nThe grounds around the cathedral\nwill be closed to automobiles at 1\no'clock except for invalids, who have\npreviously.- applied for cards. All\nother care are expected to park on\nGarfield street' at the entrance,to the\numpitheater.\nA tent with first-aid equipment,\ndoctors and nurses will he put pp on\nthe grounds to care for'emergencies.\nInspector !Clifford L' Grant or the\npolice department will have (about\ni thirty men to assist him in handling\nthe crowds. Dr'. L. W. Glazehrook,\nchairman of the ushers committee,\nwill have .one hundred men to aid in\nseating the visitors.\nASK AIICICHES\nTO HONOR FREEMAN\nThe Washington Federation of\nChurches today urged all the churches\nin the city to join in making the\nNational Cathedral open-air mass\nmeeting, on September 30. \u201cthe great\nest religious service which our city\nhas ever known.\u2019\u2019\nA letter signed by the Rev. Dr.\nGeorge N. Diffendepfer. president, and\nthe Rev. Dr. W. L. Darley, secretary\nof the federation, and sent today to\nall the Protestant churches in the\ncity stated:\n\"We are confident that many of the\nChristian people of Washington will\nbe delighted to accept this hearty In\nvitation and trust that each pastor\nwill conslred it personal for him and\nhis people. Thereby we can best show\nBishop-elect Freeman our apprecia\ntion and rightly honor our common\nLord and Master.\u2019*\nMOTHER BLAMELESS\nIN BABY\u2019S DEATH\nCoroner's Jury, However, Charges\nLack of Care, After In\nquiry at Morgue.\nA verdict asserting \u201clack of care\nbut not criminal negligence!\" jon. tha\npart of the mother was rendered by'\na coroner\u2019s jury today at the Dis\ntrict morgue fallowing the inquest\ninto the death of the female infant\nof Susie E. Edwards, eighteen years\nold, of Warrantor, Va. The mother\nwas taken back to Qal*\nlinger Hospital, where she is. under\ngoing treatment.\nDr. Herbert E. Martyn, deputy cor\noner, testified the autopsy sbowed'the\nlungs of the. child had drawn breath,\nindicating that It lived after birth,\u2019\napd that deatn Was. probably due to\"\nlack of precaution.\nDetective Alligood. Emma Me-\nOwens, colored, a maid at the Win\nston Hotel, and Mrs. Virginia Mis\nchell of 1352 Park road were wit\nnesses in the case.\nMrs. Mischell said the girl came to\nher residence about two weeks ago\n1 and that her conduct had been un\nimpeachable. She left at' 9:30 p.ni.\nSaturday, after having been ill four\ndays. The maid testified \"tp.; the find\ning of the body of the Child in ,a\nsuit case in a room occupied by -Miss\u2019\nEdwards. Detective. AUigood. said\nthe girl had given him Ahe name of\nthe man in the case.\u2022\nAssistant District Attorney \"Kelly\nrepresented the government at the\ninquest, and T. Morris Wampler ahd\nH. B. Hunt appeared for the de\nfendant.\nFINDS NEW TARIFF\nADDS TO LITIGATION\nIncrease Noted in Report by As\nsistant Attorney General in\nCharge of Customs.\nI\nLitigation over customs duties at\nAmerican ports has increased greatly\nunder the new tariff! law.\nAttorney General Daugherty made\npubHc today a review of a report by\nWilliam W. Hoppin,, assistant attor\nney general in charge of the' customs\ndivisions, showing that appeals filed\nwith the board of general appraisers\nhave more than doubled in -r*cent\nmonths. The Increased litigation was\nattributable in part, the Attorney\nGeneral said, to the general business\nrevival. _\nDuring the last fiscal year at the\nport of New York, 17,369 appeals in\ncustoms cases were filed. The report\nnoted that although some customs\ncases may be appealed to the Su\npreme Court, none is now pending.\n\u201cImporters of foreign merchandise\nrepresent important interests in this\noountry and are entitled to fair treat\nment and as expeditious a determina\ntion of the tariff act under which they\nare doing business as is practicable,\u201d\naaid the Attorney General.\n\u201cOn the other hand, the tariff law i$\nprimarily for the protection of the coun\ntry\u2019s domestic interests, and its provi\nsions must be effectively, lived up to if\nthose Interests are to be protected. For\nIf the law is unjust in its application,\nthe flexible provisions of the act should\nbe brought into play to remedy them.\nA fbir deal to both sides has been the\naim of this branch of the Department\no\u00a3 Justice.\u201d\nNote In Missouri church paper\u2014For\ntbo first time the pastor was on Sun\nday night interrupted in his sermon\nby an appeal to come and minister\nto a dying man. Needless to say he\nresponded gladly to the appeal. His\nresel l* that such o*H\u00ab are hot more\na, Transcript.\nALEXANDRIA.\nALEXANDRIA, Va.. September 19\n(Special).\u2014Gorgeous costumes, a riot\nof color, splendid lighting effects and\nexcellent acting all went to make the\npresentation of the pageant entitled \"A\nDream of Queen Esther,\" presented\nunder the auspices of the Alexandria\nPageant Association, one of the most\nelaborate ever put on. It was given\nfor the first time last night at the\ngrounds of the Cardinal Athletic Club\nat the head of King street for the bene\nfit of the Alexandria Playgrounds As\nsociation and will be repeated tonight,\nweather conditions permitting.\nSeveral thousand persons witnessed\nthe Initial performance and were loud\nin their pi-aise of the splendid cast.\nFunds derived from the pageant will\ngo to the Alexandria Playgrounds As\nsociation. Music was furnished by the\nband from Washington barracks.\nBabylonian Period.\nThe scene, was in the period of the\nBabylonian empire, 2,000 years ago. In\nthe city of Shushan in Babylonia. Tall\npines surrounding the ampltheater made\na splendid background. The loading\nrole in the pageant was taken by Miss\nCarolina Wattles, as Esther, the Jew\nish heroine, who made a pronounced\nhit. As Meeha-Zabell, Miss Mae Cav\nanaugh had a leading role and also won\nthe praise of the audience. Frank A.\nSteele, as Mordecai the Jew, was\nsplendid and carried away the audience,\nwith his excellent acting. All of the\nother participants also made a pro\nnounced hit.\nThe cast of characters as they ap\npeared in the play follow; Herald in\nthe Tower, Irvin Diener; the Holy\nCity. Miss Estelle Wentworth and\nchorus; Mordecai the Jew, Frank A.\nSteele; Meeha-Zabell, Miss Mae Cav\nanaugh .Hegai, \u2019the king's chamber\nlain, Albert Parr.-and Hannah, a Jew\nish child* Miss Catherine Power.\nShiall children. Misses Armlstead,\nWright. Cash'. Cowhlg, Demaine, Man-,\nder, Peake. Brown, Basiste, Pertdjeton,\nHatzell, cote and Root.\nEsther, a Jewish heroine, Miss Caro\nline Wattles; the Witch of Endof,\nMrs. Marian Webster; Rebecca, Mr.\nW. 11 Thomas; Miriam. Mrs. Rena\nFletcher: Deborah, Mrs. Joseph H.\nNewell; Adah. Mrs. James D. Leary;\nMartha. Mys. Edward Sweeley; Ruth,\nMrs. Alice\" Strauss, and Electa, Mrs.\nC. R. Davis.\nSecond .act \u2014-Solo dancers. Misses\nKatherine Tower, Marjorie Webster,\nPolly Arnold apd Merilyn Slentz;\nslave girls, Frances Brightwell, Jen\nnie Grady, Polly Arnold and Dulcie\nHorner.\nEgyptian Maids.\nEgyptian maids, Misses Polly Maigne,\nMildred Baker, Bernice Davidson,\nMadeline Conlon, Florence Brandt.\nHelen Sweeley, Alice Harding, Kath\nerine Fairfax, Janet Martin. Mar\ngaret Armstrong, Cletus Griffith,\nLouise Thomas. Eleanor Peake. Helen\nMyers, Pauline Strauss, Nancy King.\nGenevieve Shepperson, Dorothy Na\nbors. Mary Nabors, Thelma Red,\nLouisa Griffith, Eleanor Schwarzmann,\nKatherine Power and Florence Long.\nA Greek woman, J. William May;\na Persian woman, W. H. Callender;-\nKazma Shimeel. Miss Elizabeth Thorn\nberry; the rose maids, Hazel Kirk.\nFreda Cole. Christine West, Ethel\nBaker. Ruby Davie Haley. Velver.\nWoodfield.\nKing Ahasuerus. J. Fred Birrell;\nKoosh, a slave girl. Miss Virginia\nSteele; the Lady Ozoona, Miss Marian\nGriffith; Jakosha, Miss Virginia Wil\nkins; the Princees Zuecca, Miss Mar\ngaret Griffith; Haman, the king\u2019s\nchancellor. Dr. W. P. Caton; guards\nof the king. Smith ,Chauncey, C. T.\nGoods, Carl Rothmund.\nStaff in Charge.\nThe staff consists of Miss Helen\nNorris Cummings, general chairman;\nEdwin H. Gentry, treasurer; F. Clin\nton Knight, tickets: C. M. Horgan,\npublicity; E. A. Feldkeller and B. A.\nSelple, lighting; Mr. Wells, usher;\nEverett Hellmuth, grounds; Albert\nParr, stage director; Mrs. Alice\nStrauss, director of children\u2019s group;\nMiss Marjorie Webster, director of\nballet; Carl Rothmund, properties;\nCapt. P. L. Lewis, commander of\noand; Messrs. Stannard and Yassel,\ndirectors; Miss Mamie Conlon. prompt\ner; Frank A. Steele, general director.\nTonight A. J. Rhodes will take the\npart of herald in the tower. The\nmusical program was under, the di\nrection of Miss Estelle yTerttworth.\nRoccb Verri sang a solo during *he\nperformance.\nThe bronze drinking fountain\nerected April 1, 1912, In the center\nof- Cameron and Royal streets by\nMount Vernon Chapter, Daughters of\nthe American Revolution, this iclty,\nwhich waa taken down about three\nyears ago. has been re-erected at\nthe southwest corner of Fairfax and\nCameron streets. The fountain is\nnow*in position and after the pipes\nare connected water will be turned\non.\nOwing to the fact that the foun\ntain had been considerably damaged\nand also that it leaked, it was taken\ndown and since then has been stored\nin the city hall building.\nSeveral months ago a committee of\nladles of the local chapter of the\nD. A. R. appealed to the city council\nand urged that it be re-erected at\nthe comer where it waa originally\nplaced or else at some other comer\nnearby. The result waa the selec\ntion of the corner where it now\nstands.\u2019\n\u2022\u2018Human Fly\u201d Postpone* Performance.\nOwing to the fact that the histori\ncal pageant will be repeated tonight\nthe performance of Harry Gardner,\n\u201cthe human fly,\u201d who was scheduled\nto climb the Alexandria Gazette build\ning and the Alexandria National Bank\nbuilding at 7:30 o'clock tonight, has\nbeen postponed until tomorrow night\nat the pame hour. This waa decided\nup t cm at a meeting of Alexandria Post,\nNo. VB4. American Legion, and the\nwomen's auxiliary to the legion at\na.-, rheatlng held last night in the\nroOitia of the chamber of commerce.\nTh*-members of .the legion and auxil\niary will meet tomorrow night at 7\no\u2019clock in the Gaeztte building and\ncomplete-.atrangementa for handling\nthe crowd expected. A spotlight will\nbe played on Gardner aa he climbs\nboth buildings. He will wear a white\nduck suit. The street during his per\nformance will be closed to traffic.\nTom Kippur Services.\nVom Kippur, a day of atonement\nand fasting, will be observed with\nservices in the synagogue at 7:30\no\u2019clock tonight, which will be con\nducted by Rabbi Teaxey of Cincinnati,\nand Services also wlli be held at 10\no'clock tomorrow morning. The stores\nof the Hebrews of this city will close\nat 6 o'clock this evening and will not\nreopen until Friday morning.\nThe funeral of Mrs. Marian P. A.\nGarneh wife of John W. Garner, who\ndied Monday night, will take place\nat 4 o\u2019clock tomorrow afternoon from\nher late residence, 413 South Fairfax\nstreet. Services will be conducted\nby Rev. E. M. Delaney, pastor of the\nSecond Presbyterian Church, and\nburial will bo in Ivy Hill cemetery.\nThe deceased, besides her husband,\nis survived by the following children:\nCorporation Attorney JL Noel Garner,\nMiss Nettle Gamer and Mrs. George\nA. Windsor.\nLast rites for Mrs. Lucy Jane Cur\ntis. widow of George T, Curtis, who\ntiled Monday night, will be held at\n2 o\u2019clock tojWpyrow afternoon at the\nresidence oDaer daughter, Mrs. James\nHaywood, 72* Gibbon street, and will\nbe conducted by\u2019\u2019 ReV, Edgar Car\npenter, rector of Grace Episcopal\nChurch, and: burial. will, be In; Union\ncemetery.\nThe funeral of John M. Harlow,\nwho died Monday night, will be held\nat 9:46 o\u2019clock, tomorrow morning\nfrom St. Mary\u2019s Catholic Church and\nburial will be In St Mary\u2019s cemetery.\nThe deceased was a member of Wash\nington Lodge of Elks, No. 15.\nJohn M. Francis and wife sold\nto Ida L. Penn a house and lot on\nthe west side of Fairfax between\nWilkes and Gibbon streets. A deed\nof conveyance today was placed on\nrecord in the office of the clerk of\nthe court.\nWIFE ANSWERS RHINE.\nMrs. Anna Hilda Rhine today filed an\nanswer to the cross-petition of her hus\nband, Charles W. Rhine, for an abso\nlute divorce from her.\nShe denies charges of misconduct al\nleged by the husband and renews\ncharges which she made against him In\nher original suit for a limited divorce.\nThe husband is a foremaw for a prom\ninent firm' of banders realtors.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 19, 1923.\nSEPARATE SEWER\n\u2019.w-\nZONE ADVOCATED\nReport of Engineering Com\nmittee of Arlington Dis\ntrict Is Made.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star,\nCLARENDON, Va., September 19.\nA recommendation that the zoning\nplan for sewering Arlington county\nbe changed to make each natural\ndrainage area a separate sewer zone\nwas the chief feature of the report\nof the engineering committee of Ar\nlington district sanitary commission\nof Zones 6 and 10. made to a\nof the commission at the courthouse\nlast night.\nThe report'further recommends that\nthe tfunk lines and disposal plants\nfor these area* he established at the\nexpense of the citizens In the respec\ntive areas, and that all construction\nwork be under the supervision of the\nsanitary commission.\nA resolution requesting the board\nof supervisors of the county to have\nthe sanitary engineer prepare and\nhave published a report of his activi\nties in connection with the operation\nof the Jesse sanitary law, as pro\nvided, by the law, was adopted by the\nmeeting.,\nCommission Not Antagonistic,\nIt was emphatically pointed out at,\nthe meeting that the sanitary com\nmission is in no way antagonistic to\nthe proposal to establish modern\nsewer systems in the county, but is\nsimply working to the end that the\nproject will be consummated to the\nentire satisfaction of all concerned.\nAll investigations of the commission,\nit wan said, are being made for the\npurpose of keeping the people of the\nsections to be affected informed on\nall phases so that; they may vote in\ntelligently when tha matter of bond\ning for the improvements is brought\nito an election.\nF. E. Plymale of Fort Myef Heights,\nchairman of the commission, presided\nat last night\u2019s meeting.. The report\nof the engineers\u2019 committee was made\nby 1t\u00bb chairman, R. P. Hough. Other\nmembers of the committee are Harry\nC. Saffell, N. D. Mitchell, M. C. Mc-\nShea and J. O. Johnson.\nBelief Contribution*.\nContinuing its drive for Japaness\nrelief funds the Arlington Chapter.\nAmerican Red Cross, reports the fol\nlowing contributions in addition to\nthe $731.02 previously reported, mak\ning the total to date $887.00;\nCharles T. Jesse, $10; H- I*. s *\u2122P son\n$5; Columbia Lodge. NO. 285, or\nClarendon. $25; Howard Smoot. $1;\nMrs Pcrrott. 50 cents; Aaron Smith,\nMrs: W. H. Norton'. $1; G. H. Gay, $1;\nBible class of Aurora Hills. $5; Mrs.\nRoy Reeve, $1; Paul M. Cassin, 511\nLouis Slorck. $1; E. J. Skidmore, slj\nC. W. Tarbutton, $1; A. D. Davis, $1;\nVincent Clayton, $1; Mra. Cassin, $1;\njossle Everett. $1; W. T. Clayton. $5;\nCash, $2.23; Mr. and Mrs. J. H. Cris\nwell. $5; Gov. Richard Bennett So\nciety Children American Revolution,\n$5; Alexandria Light and Power Com\npany. Clarendon office. $10; Harry R.\nThomas, 15, and St. George\u2019s Episcopal\nChurch. $2. In addition to $39 already\ncontributed.\nThomas J. De Lashmutt. chairman\nof the hoard of supervisors and mem\nber of the board from Arlington dis\ntrict. settled ail speculation as to\nwhether or not he would be a can\ndidate to succeed himself In the com\ning November elections, which has\nbeen rife in the district for several\nmonths, by casting his hat into the\nring yesterday. There are five other\ncandidates already in the field for\nthis office, \u2019j,\nROCKVILLE.\nROCKVILLE, Md.. September 1$\n(Special).\u2014Upon being found guilty\nin the police court here of assaulting\nRaymond Miles, a young negro, at a\ndance at Bethesda, this county, last\nSaturday night, by shooting him with\na revolver. Prince Rice, also colored,\nwas sentenced by Judge Samuel Riggs\nto two years in the house of correc\ntion. The two had a controversy over\na trivial matter and Rice took a shot\nat Miles, the bullet leaning the skin\nslightly in close proximity to the\nheart. On a charge of carrying a con\ncealed weapon Rice was given an\nadditional year in the same institu\ntion.\nMarriage License* Issued.\nLicenses to have been issued\nby the clerk of the circuit court'here\nto the following: Robert Shifflett of\nBon Aire, Va., and Virginia Unt of\nWashington; Moses L. Harris and\nMary E. Corcoran, both of Worcester,\nMass.; Floyd White and Jessie Cline*\nboth of Warrsnton, Va.; Charles Lester\nTaylor, Jr. of Washington and Wlllmai\nDiem of Atlantic City; N. J.:-WUUaYn F,\nDonaldson and Mary E. Frye, both of\nPotomac, Md.\nFor violations of the motor vehicle\nregulations the following have paid\nfines or forfeited collaterals In the\npolice court here: Thurman Pierce.\nEdward Dlngley. Katherine A. Burke\nand Lawrence Offutt, $12.50 each; B.\nF. Barkdoll, $10: Joseph Johnson, C.\nJ. Burgess and Robert Cunningham,\n$7.60 each.\nHome Bunt* Down,\nEarly Monday evening the residence\nof Mrs. Edna Burroughs, near Poto\nmac, this county, was destroyed by\nfire, together With virtually all of the\nfurniture, about SSO in cash and all\nclothing of the members of the family\nexcept what they were wearing at\nthe time. The Rockville volunteer\nfiremen responded to the alarm, but\narrived too late to save anything.\nThe loss is placed at about $3,000, a\nsmall part of whleh Is covered by In\nsuranco. It is not known what caused\nthe fire.\nThe home of Walter and Harry\nMyers in the same neighborhood, also\ncaught fire on Monday. Neighbors\nformed themselves into a bucket\nbrigade and succeded in subduing the\nflames, not, however, until a Urge\nportion of the roof had been destroy*\ned. The loss els\u2018understood to havO\nbeen about SSOO, and covered by ln+\nsurance. No one waa at home at the\ntime the fire broke out, and what\ncaused It Ik not known..\u2022\nU. S. SEEKS $2,500,000 i\nFROM BETHLEHEM CORE\nShip Board Claims Shipbuilding\nCompany Was Overpaid on\nWar Contract.\nPalling to reach a settlement by ne\ngotiation, the Shipping Board has in\nstructed its legal department to pre\npare suit against the Bethlehem Ship\nbuilding Corporation for recovery of\nabout $2,500,000 alleged to have been\noverpaid under that firm\u2019s war con\ntracts.\nIf sustained in the courts the point\nraised by the board may throw open\nfor legal review scores of war con\ntracts involving hundreds of millions\nof dollars. In brief, the issue is said\nto be whether the government can\nnot limit the amount of profits to bs\ntaken by a corporation or Individual\nIn return lor emergency services.\nCHURCH TO'HEAR LECTURE\n\nA lecture, entitled \u201cChristian\nScience; The Science of Right Living,\"\nwill be delivered Friday evening at\n8 o\u2019clock at First Church of Christ,\nScientist. Columbia road and Euclid\nstreet, by Prof. Hermann S. Herlng,\nC. S. 8., of Boston, Mass.\nThe lecturer will be Introduced by\nElmer 1. Baldwin, first reader of First\nChurch of this city, under whose\nauspices the lecture will be given.\nThe public to Invited, and the lecture\nis free.\nBANS CONCERTS.\nToday at 4:30 p.m., at United\nStates Capitol, by the United\nStates \u2018Marine Band; WUU.am\nH. Santclmann, leader: Taylor\nBranson, second lefidfer.\nProgram:\nOverture, \"Rlenzl\u201d Wagner\nNocturne, \"Dreams of Love,\"\nLiszt\nCornet solo, \"Lost Chord,\u201d\nSullivan\nMusician Arthur S. Wltcomb.\nTwo movements from the sym\nphony, \u201cFrom the New\nWorld\u201d Dvorak\n(a) Largo.\n(b) Scherzo.\nEntrance of the gods In Wal\nhall, from \"The Valkyrie,\"\nWagner\n\"Invitation to the\u2019Dance,\"\nWeber-Welngartner\nTranscribed for military band\nby William H. Santelmann.\n\"Hungarian Rhapsody No. 14.\u201d\nLiszt\n\"The Star Spangled Banner.\u201d\nToday at 7:30 p.m., at Chevy\nChase Circle, by the Washing\nton Boys\u2019 Independent Band;\nChester Hayes, director.\nProgram:\nMarch, \"Washington Post,\u201d\nSousa\nOverture, \"Debutante\u201d.',.. .Lee\nWaliz, \u201cBell Island\u201d-.,... fKing\nFox trot, \u201cYou Tell Her X Stut\nter\u201d Hall\nCornet solo, \"Conqueror\u201d. .Bell\nMusician Earl Smallwood.\nMarch, \"Safety\u201d Bennett\nSerenade, \"Mooning\u201d Neil\nMarch, \"National Emblem,\"\nBagley\n\"The Star Spangled Banner.\u201d\nConcert by the United States\nSoldiers\u2019 Home Band at the\nbandstand. Soldiers\u2019 Home, thin\nevening, beginning at 5:50!\nv o\u2019clock. John' S. M. Zimmer\nmann, bandmaster-\nMarch, \"The .Sword of\nDamocles\u201d K Boehnlein\nOverture. \"Bohetfaian Girl\u201d.Balfe\nEntr'acte\n(a) \"The Narcissus\" Nevin\n(b) \"A Broken\nMe10dy\u201d...,. Van Biene\nScenes from opera, \"Love\nTales of Count Huff\nman\u201d. ..'.Offenbach\nPox trot, Sauqe\u201d. .Freed\nWaltz novelty, \"Kis\u00ab-a-\nMiss\u201d. .V Baron\nFinale,, \u201cYea, We Have No\nBananas\u201d'. .Silver\n\"The Star Spangled Banner\u201d\nFIGHT ARENA FIRE\nLAID TOjNCENDIARY\nProtest Meeting Called by\nLaw and Order League in\nChesapeake Junction Blaze.\nFire, of apparently incendiary ori\ngin, damaged the Maryland Park fight\narena at Chesapeake Junction, Md., to\nthe extent of about <3,500 laat night.\nThis estimate was made by Benjamin\nFranklin of Baltimore, in charge of\nthe arena.\nFranklin said that a number of chairs\nas well as the lefthand portion of.\nthe arena had been wrecked. Investi\ngation today, tended to confirm the\ntheory of Incendiarism, when\u2018it was\nfound that the flames had traveled\nin two distinct pathways leaving a\nwide gap of unburned material be\ntween them.\nProtest Meeting Called. _\nThe Law and Order League \u2019of\nPrince Oeoijres county has called a\nmass fneellng tonight In the Seat\nPleasant Public School to protest,\naccording to Lindsay S. Perkins,\nleague leader, against \"alleged In\ncendiarism responsible for the blaze.\u201d\nMr. Perkins pointed o> t today that\nwhile the Law and Order League,\ntogether with citizens of Seat Pleas\nant generally, are fighting the estab\nlishment of a boxing arena at Seat\nPleasant, it Is equally opposed to\nillegal methods of preventing the\nholding of prize fights.\nA petition protesting against the\nstaging of fights in the new arena\nwas forwarded recently to the Mary\nland boxing commission.\u00bb Jt was\nsigned by 1.000 \"taxpayers\u201d\nArrangements to check up rn the\ndamage which was coveted by in\nsurance and to repair the damaged\nportion of the arena had \u2018already\nstarted this afternoon. It is believed\nthat all of the damage' will-be re\npaired within* the next ten days, Mr.\nFranklin said.\nFranklin sajd that he had been\nInformed today a reward of SSOO was\nto be offered }>y persqnsr p<. the vicin\nity for the apprehension of any one\nImplicated in the- believed arson..\nMORE FREE PRINCIPALS,\nSORT. BALLOU\u2019S PROGRAM\nAppointment of five additional ad\nministrative or free principals will\nbe recommended to the board of edu\ncation at Its meeting this afternoon\nby Supt. of Schools Frank W. Ballou.\nThere are now thlrty-slx adminis\ntrative principals In the school serv\nice\u2014twenty-six white and ten col\nored\u2014and it la the plan of the su\nperintendent to increase this number\nfrom time to time when the oppor\ntunity presents Itself through the\ntransfer, resignation or retirement of\nteaching principals.\n,One of the developments of the\nschool system during the Incumbency\nof Dr. Ballou has been the Increase\nIn the size of elementary school build\nings and the union of adjoining build\nings, ipoklng'toward the ultimate dis\nplacement of the present teaching\nprincipal In the-eight-room school by\na free or administrative principal of\na building or group of buildings with\nsixteen or more classrooms. These\nadministrative principals assume some\nof the local direction of education\nwithin the school which has been\nformerly carried by the supervising\nprincipal.\nj\n\n5\nIT\nI II\nWfTsm R| HI\nWARD STORY FALSE.\nCOUNSEL ADMITS\nBy the Associated Press.\nWHITE PLAINS, N. Y., September\n18.\u2014Several witnesses for the state\nin the trial of Walter S. Ward, mil\nlionaire baker, for the murder of\nClarence Peters today testified to\nthe circumstances of the finding of\nPeters' body on a lonely road seven\nteen months ago.\nDr. Henry J. Vler, one of the phy\nsicians who performed the autopsy,\nwas recalled to tilt, stand. He would\nnot estimate how far away Ward had\nstood when he fired the shot which\nkilled the former marine. Ward. In\nhis version of the shooting, said he\nstood a considerable distance from\nPeters, but the prosecution today at\ntempted to prove the shot was fired\nat close range.\nPorto Rican* Attend.\nM. Roduguez-Serra. justice of the\nsupreme court of Porto Rico, and\nHenry O. Molina, president of the\nPorto Rican Bar Association, at\ntended the trial at the invitation of\nSupreme Court Justice Wagner, pre\nsiding judge.\nThe extraordinary grand jury\nwhich is investigating Peters\u2019 death\nwa\u00ab in session In a room directly un\nder that in which the trial was con\noucted. Ralph D. Ward, brother of\nthe defendant, and Attorney General\nSherman left court to appear before\nthe grand jury, a -A\nInterett ln the* trial of Walter S.\nWard, rich baker, for the murder of\nClarence Peters, former marine in\ncreased because of the admission of\nIsaac N, Mills, chief counsel for the\ndefense, that part of Ward\u2019s story\ncould not be true.\nWard In his first story to the\nauthorities of the events leading up\nto the tragedy said Peters was with\nthe. mysterious \u201cRoss\" ahd \u201cRogers,\"\nwho have neve#- been found, oh the\nevening before the\u2019 shooting. The\nstate was said to Lave jproof of the\nfact that on night. In question\nPeters was on a train somewhere be\ntween Richmond,, and Washing\nton.\nTapestry FZT Wa\u00ab, OT Boys\u2019 SI.OO\nI l\nBeautifully mercerized qual- illl,\u00ae many colors, styles and pat-\nr ity in the popular green. 2 J A i _ ah 5\nyards long.. W* BIOSIB Seventh Street terns. All sizes.\nAnother Underprice Purchase of\n|JP QUALITY TRIMMED HATS\nw|(7 Panne Velvet, Lyons Velvet, Embroidered Velvet\niMy Duplicating Monday\u2019s brilliant underselling\nW feat\u2014with this new shipment of Fashion\u2019s new- v/1111111l\nest in fall millinery to sell at $3.50. The sale Jjj\nprice is far short of the real values \u2